## 8. The Lindy Effect and the Organism's Long-Term Viability

The **Lindy Effect** proposes that the future life expectancy of non-perishable things is proportional to their current age. The longer something has survived, the longer it is likely to continue to survive. This principle, formalized by Nassim Taleb, applies with particular force to Bitcoin. [11](#user-content-fn-11)

Bitcoin (BSV) has now survived for over sixteen years, weathering every conceivable form of attack: technical exploits, regulatory bans, exchange failures, contentious forks, media campaigns, and the opposition of the most powerful financial institutions in the world. Each year of survival increases the Lindy-predicted future lifespan. Each attack that fails to kill the organism strengthens confidence in its resilience.

The BTC protocol's long-term viability is, by contrast, deeply uncertain. Its security model depends on an ever-rising price to compensate miners for their work, since the artificial block size limit prevents the network from generating sufficient fee revenue. This is not a sustainable model. As the block subsidy continues to decline with each halving, the BTC network will face a growing security crisis. The organism's metabolism is insufficient to sustain it.

Bitcoin (BSV), with its unbounded block size and low transaction fees, has a sustainable long-term economic model. As the network grows and transaction volume increases, the fee revenue available to miners will grow proportionally. The organism's metabolism is designed to scale with its growth, ensuring its long-term survival.

