## 9. Bitcoin as an Extended Phenotype of Humanity

Richard Dawkins introduced the concept of the **extended phenotype** in his 1982 book of the same name, arguing that the effects of a gene extend beyond the organism's body into the environment. [12](#user-content-fn-12) A beaver's dam is part of the beaver's extended phenotype; the intricate architecture of a termite mound is part of the termite's extended phenotype. These structures are expressions of the organism's genetic code, shaped by natural selection to serve the organism's survival and reproduction.

Bitcoin can be understood as a kind of extended phenotype for humanity, a structure built by humans, shaped by the evolutionary pressures of economic competition and game theory, that serves the survival and flourishing of its human builders. The Bitcoin blockchain is a monument to human ingenuity, a structure that will outlast any individual, any corporation, or any government.

The academic paper by Schmalzried (2024) situates this co-evolutionary process within the broader context of humanity's evolution as a "superorganism," a collective entity whose behavior is shaped by the emergent dynamics of millions of interacting individuals. Drawing on Nate Hagens' superorganism framework and Francis Heylighen's "global brain" theory, Schmalzried argues that blockchain technology, and Bitcoin in particular, represents a new layer of coordination infrastructure for the human superorganism, a nervous system for global economic activity that operates without central control. [13](#user-content-fn-13)

Bitcoin (BSV), as the original and unmodified Bitcoin, is the most complete expression of this vision. It is the blockchain that can serve as the global data infrastructure for all human activity, the single, honest ledger that the world has been waiting for.

